# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: physx
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:physx/collision-response] In the context of classical mechanics simulations and physics engines employed within video games, **collision response** deals with models and algorithms for simulating the changes in the motion of two solid bodies following collision and other forms of contact.
[src:physx/collision-response] Two rigid bodies in unconstrained motion, potentially under the action of forces, may be modelled by solving their equations of motion using numerical integration techniques.
[src:physx/collision-response] On collision, the kinetic properties of two such bodies seem to undergo an instantaneous change, typically resulting in the bodies rebounding away from each other, sliding, or settling into relative static contact, depending on the elasticity of the materials and the configuration of the collision.
[src:physx/collision-response] The origin of the rebound phenomenon, or *reaction*, may be traced to the behaviour of real bodies that, unlike their perfectly rigid idealised counterparts, do undergo minor compression on collision, followed by expansion, prior to separation.
[src:physx/collision-response] The compression phase converts the kinetic energy of the bodies into potential energy and to an extent, heat.
[src:physx/collision-response] The expansion phase converts the potential energy back to kinetic energy.
[src:physx/collision-response] The degree of relative kinetic energy retained after a collision, termed the *restitution*, is dependent on the elasticity of the bodies‟ materials.
[src:physx/collision-response] The coefficient of restitution between two given materials is modeled as the ratio $e\in [0..1]$ of the relative post-collision speed of a point of contact along the contact normal, with respect to the relative pre-collision speed of the same point along the same normal.
[src:physx/collision-response] These coefficients are typically determined empirically for different material pairs, such as wood against concrete or rubber against wood.
[src:physx/collision-response] Values for e close to zero indicate inelastic collisions such as a piece of soft clay hitting the floor, whereas values close to one represent highly elastic collisions, such as a rubber ball bouncing off a wall.
[src:physx/collision-response] The kinetic energy loss is relative to one body with respect to the other.
[src:physx/collision-response] Thus the total momentum of both bodies with respect to some common reference is unchanged after the collision, in line with the principle of *conservation of momentum*.
[src:physx/collision-response] Another important contact phenomenon is surface-to-surface friction, a force that impedes the relative motion of two surfaces in contact, or that of a body in a fluid.
[src:physx/collision-response] In this section we discuss surface-to-surface friction of two bodies in relative static contact or sliding contact.
[src:physx/collision-response] In the real world, friction is due to the imperfect microstructure of surfaces whose protrusions interlock into each other, generating reactive forces tangential to the surfaces.
[src:physx/collision-response] To overcome the friction between two bodies in static contact, the surfaces must somehow lift away from each other.
[src:physx/collision-response] Once in motion, the degree of surface affinity is reduced and hence bodies in sliding motion tend to offer lesser resistance to motion.
[src:physx/collision-response] These two categories of friction are respectively termed *static friction* and *dynamic friction*.
[src:physx/collision-response] It is a force which is applied to an object by another object or by a person.
[src:physx/collision-response] The direction of the applied force depends on how the force is applied.
[src:physx/collision-response] It is the support force exerted upon an object which is in contact with another stable object.
[src:physx/collision-response] Normal force is sometimes referred to as the pressing force since its action presses the surface together.
[src:physx/collision-response] Normal force is always directed towards the object and acts perpendicularly with the applied force.
[src:physx/collision-response] It is the force exerted by a surface as an object moves across it or makes an effort to move across it.
[src:physx/collision-response] The friction force opposes the motion of the object.
[src:physx/collision-response] Friction results when two surfaces are pressed together closely, causing attractive intermolecular forces between the molecules of the two different surface.
[src:physx/collision-response] As such, friction depends upon the nature of the two surfaces and upon the degree to which they are pressed together.
[src:physx/collision-response] Friction always acts parallel to the surface in contact and opposite the direction of motion.
[src:physx/collision-response] The friction force can be calculated using the equation.
[src:physx/collision-response] For fixed impulse $\mathbf {j}$ , the equation suggests that $t_{1}\rightarrow t_{0}\Rightarrow \left|\mathbf {f} \right|\rightarrow \infty$ , that is, a smaller time interval must be compensated by a stronger reaction force to achieve the same impulse.
[src:physx/collision-response] When modelling a collision between idealized rigid bodies, it is impractical to simulate the compression and expansion phases of the body geometry over the collision time interval.
[src:physx/collision-response] exists and is equal to $\mathbf {j}$ , the notion of *instantaneous impulses* may be introduced to simulate an instantaneous change in velocity after a collision.
[src:physx/collision-response] By deduction from the principle of action and reaction, if the collision impulse applied by the first body on the second body at a contact point $\mathbf {p} _{r}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ is $\mathbf {j} _{r}$ , the counter impulse applied by the second body on the first is $-\mathbf {j} _{r}$ .
[src:physx/collision-response] In the subsequent formulas, $\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ is always assumed to point away from body 1 and towards body 2 at the contact point.
[src:physx/collision-response] where, for the i th body, $\mathbf {v} _{i}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ is the pre-collision linear velocity, $\mathbf {v'} _{i}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ is the post-collision linear velocity.
[src:physx/collision-response] Compute the reaction impulse vector $\mathbf {j} _{r}$ in terms of its magnitude $j_{r}$ and contact normal $\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ using $\mathbf {j} _{r}=j_{r}\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ .
[src:physx/collision-response] One of the most popular models for describing friction is the Coulomb friction model.
[src:physx/collision-response] This model defines coefficients of static friction ${\mu }_{s}\in \mathbb {R}$ and dynamic friction ${\mu }_{d}\in \mathbb {R}$ such that ${\mu }_{s}>{\mu }_{d}$ .
[src:physx/collision-response] These coefficients describe the two types of friction forces in terms of the reaction forces acting on the bodies.
[src:physx/collision-response] The value $f_{s}$ defines a maximum magnitude for the friction force required to counter the tangential component of any external sum force applied on a relatively static body, such that it remains static.
[src:physx/collision-response] Thus, if the external force is large enough, static friction is unable to fully counter this force, at which point the body gains velocity and becomes subject to dynamic friction of magnitude $f_{d}$ acting against the sliding velocity.
[src:physx/collision-response] The Coulomb friction model effectively defines a friction cone within which the tangential component of a force exerted by one body on the surface of another in static contact, is countered by an equal and opposite force such that the static configuration is maintained.
[src:physx/collision-response] Conversely, if the force falls outside the cone, static friction gives way to dynamic friction.
[src:physx/collision-response] where $\mathbf {f} _{e}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ is the sum of all external forces on the body.
[src:physx/collision-response] The multi-case definition of $\mathbf {\hat {t}}$ is required for robustly computing the actual friction force $\mathbf {f} _{f}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ for both the general and particular states of contact.
[src:physx/collision-response] Informally, the first case computes the tangent vector along the relative velocity component perpendicular to the contact normal $\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ .
[src:physx/collision-response] If this component is zero, the second case derives $\mathbf {\hat {t}}$ in terms of the tangent component of the external force $\mathbf {f} _{e}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ .
[src:physx/collision-response] If there is no tangential velocity or external forces, then no friction is assumed, and $\mathbf {\hat {t}}$ may be set to the zero vector.
[src:physx/collision-response] Equations (6a), (6b), (7) and (8) describe the Coulomb friction model in terms of forces.
[src:physx/collision-response] where $j_{r}=|\mathbf {j} _{r}|$ is the magnitude of the reaction impulse acting along contact normal $\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ .
[src:physx/collision-response] Equations (5) and (10) define an impulse-based contact model that is ideal for impulse-based simulations.
[src:physx/collision-response] When using this model, care must be taken in the choice of ${\mu }_{s}$ and ${\mu }_{d}$ as higher values may introduce additional kinetic energy into the system.
[src:physx/game-physics] There are two central types of physics simulations: rigid body and soft-body simulators.
[src:physx/game-physics] In a rigid body simulation objects are grouped into categories based on how they should interact and are less performance intensive.
[src:physx/game-physics] Soft-body physics involves simulating individual sections of each object such that it behaves in a more realistic way.
[src:physx/game-physics] A common aspect of computer games that model some type of conflict is the explosion.
[src:physx/game-physics] Early computer games used the simple expedient of repeating the same explosion in each circumstance.
[src:physx/game-physics] However, in the real world an explosion can vary depending on the terrain, altitude of the explosion, and the type of solid bodies being impacted.
[src:physx/game-physics] Depending on the processing power available, the effects of the explosion can be modeled as the split and shattered components propelled by the expanding gas.
[src:physx/game-physics] This is modelled by means of a particle system simulation.
[src:physx/game-physics] A particle system model allows a variety of other physical phenomena to be simulated, including smoke, moving water, precipitation, and so forth.
[src:physx/game-physics] The individual particles within the system are modelled using the other elements of the physics simulation rules, with the limitation that the number of particles that can be simulated is restricted by the computing power of the hardware.
[src:physx/game-physics] Thus explosions may need to be modelled as a small set of large particles, rather than the more accurate huge number of fine particles.
[src:physx/game-physics] This is a procedural animation and simulation technique to display the movement of a character when killed.
[src:physx/game-physics] It treats the character's body as a series of rigid bones connected together with hinges at the joints.
[src:physx/game-physics] The simulation models what happens to the body as it collapses to the ground.
[src:physx/game-physics] More sophisticated physics models of creature movement and collision interactions require greater level of computing power and a more accurate simulation of solids, liquids, and hydrodynamics.
[src:physx/game-physics] The modelled articulated systems can then reproduce the effects of skeleton, muscles, tendons, and other physiological components.
[src:physx/game-physics] Some games, such as Boneworks and Half-Life 2, apply forces to individual joints that allow ragdolls to move and behave like humanoids with fully procedural animations.
[src:physx/game-physics] This allows to, for example, knock an enemy down or grab each individual joint and move it around and the physics-based animation would adapt accordingly, which wouldn't be possible with conventional means.
[src:physx/game-physics] This method is called active ragdolls and is often used in combination with inverse kinematics.
[src:physx/game-physics] Projectiles, such as arrows or bullets, often travel at very high speeds.
[src:physx/game-physics] This creates problems with collisions - sometimes the projectile travels so fast that it simply goes past a thin object without ever detecting that it has collided with it.
[src:physx/game-physics] Before, this was solved with ray-casting, which does not require the creation of a physical projectile.
[src:physx/game-physics] However, simply shooting a ray in the direction that the weapon is aiming at is not particularly realistic, which is why modern games often create a physical projectile that can be affected by gravity and other forces.
[src:physx/game-physics] This projectile uses a form of continuous collision detection to make sure that the above-stated problem will not occur (at the cost of inferior performance), since more complex calculations are required to perform such a task.
[src:physx/game-physics] Games such as FIFA 14 require accurate projectile physics for objects such as the soccer ball.
[src:physx/game-physics] In FIFA 14, developers were required to fix code related to the drag coefficient which was inaccurate in previous games, leading to a much more realistic simulation of a real ball.
[src:physx/havok-software] In 2008, Havok was honored at the 59th Annual Technology & Engineering Emmy Awards for advancing the development of physics engines in electronic entertainment.
[src:physx/havok-software] Telekynesis Research Limited was founded in 1998 by two university students Hugh Reynolds and Steven Collins of the computer science department in Trinity College, Dublin who would form the studio based in Dublin, Ireland.
[src:physx/havok-software] The software was originally named **Omniate** initially, but was then renamed to Havok (Named after the Marvel X-Men character).
[src:physx/havok-software] Version 1.0 of the Havok SDK was unveiled at the Game Developers Conference (GDC) in March 2000.
[src:physx/havok-software] In 1999, a German-software company based in Munich had developed their own physics engine called **Ipion Virtual Physics**, it was a real-time middleware physics engine developed in the late 1990s by the German software company Ipion Software.
[src:physx/havok-software] Designed for the simulation of rigid body dynamics in video games and interactive media, it was a significant early competitor in the physics middleware market along with MathEngine.
[src:physx/havok-software] In June 2000, Ipion was acquired by Havok, and its core technologies were subsequently integrated into the **Havok Physics** engine.
[src:physx/havok-software] The development of the Virtual Physics engine was led by chief architect Oliver Strunk and a decentralized team of engineers across Germany.
[src:physx/havok-software] Developed in C++, the engine was built with cross-platform compatibility in mind, supporting Microsoft Windows, Linux, Solaris, and the PlayStation 2 console.
[src:physx/havok-software] On June 8, 2000, the Irish company Havok acquired Ipion.
[src:physx/havok-software] This merger transformed the Ipion team into Havok's Munich office, marking the company's third international location after Dublin and Palo Alto.
[src:physx/havok-software] The acquisition was a pivotal moment in the industry, as the sophisticated algorithms of the Ipion Virtual Physics SDK became the technological foundation for Havok's 1.5 release and beyond.
[src:physx/havok-software] Ipion was noted for its advanced handling of complex physical interactions for the era.
[src:physx/havok-software] At the time of its commercial peak, the Ipion SDK was licensed for approximately $50,000 to $60,000 per project.
[src:physx/havok-software] The software package provided developers with a 76-page technical manual and a comprehensive C++ library.
[src:physx/havok-software] Ipion's most visible legacy is found in the 3DMark 2001 SE benchmark.
[src:physx/havok-software] The software's "Game 4" and "Physics Feature" tests utilized the Ipion engine to demonstrate high-end hardware capabilities through complex rigid body simulations.
[src:physx/havok-software] It was also utilized in several retail titles, including the 2001 racing game *Route 66* (known internationally as *USA Racer*).
[src:physx/havok-software] Following the Havok merger, the Ipion name was phased out, though its influence persists in modern physics simulations through its direct contribution to the Havok engine.
[src:physx/havok-software] It is also famously used in *Half-Life 2*, albeit heavily modified by Valve as VPhysics (VPhysics uses custom proprietary code from Valve, with additional Havok code for constraints and memory optimized partial polytype).
[src:physx/havok-software] *Half-Life 2* is lauded as one of the early licensees of a real-time physics middleware such as the Ipion Virtual Physics early in its development cycle at the start of the millennium.
[src:physx/havok-software] The first game to utilize Havok was a game released in 1999 called London Racer developed by Davilex Games which had a long partnership with Havok/IVP.
[src:physx/havok-software] The Havok SDK is multi-platform by nature and is always updated to run on the majority of the latest platforms.
[src:physx/havok-software] Licensees are given access to most of the C/C++ source-code, giving them the freedom to customize the engine's features, or port it to different platforms although some libraries are only provided in binary format.
[src:physx/havok-software] In March 2011, Havok showed off a version of the Havok physics engine designed for use with the Sony Xperia Play, or more specifically, Android 2.3.
[src:physx/havok-software] During Microsoft's BUILD 2012 conference, Havok unveiled a full technology suite for Windows 8, Windows RT, Windows Phone 8 and later Windows 10.
[src:physx/havok-software] As of February 2023, Havok supports 18 targets across 10 platforms.
[src:physx/havok-software] These platforms include: Windows, Linux, Xbox Series S/X, PlayStation 5, iOS, Nintendo Switch and Android.
[src:physx/havok-software] In 2019, Unity and Havok signed a partnership to build a complete physics solution for DOTS-based projects in Unity.
[src:physx/havok-software] This was completed and released as production ready in December 2022.
[src:physx/havok-software] Havok maintains integrations for all of their products to Epic's Unreal Engine.
[src:physx/havok-software] Havok Physics can be used to replace the inbuilt physics engine (Chaos Physics) at an engine level, while Havok Navigation is a stand-alone plugin, and Havok Cloth is a separate tool that works alongside the engine.
[src:physx/havok-software] In April 2023, Babylon.js 6.0 was released with a physics implementation by Havok.
[src:physx/havok-software] This implementation was released as a WASM plugin and involved an overhaul of the Babylon.js Physics API.
[src:physx/havok-software] The first game to use Havok Physics was *London Racer* in 1999 by Davilex Games.
[src:physx/havok-software] In 2023, Havok products were used in twelve of the top twenty best selling video games in the United States.
[src:physx/havok-software] Havok supplies tools (the "Havok Content Tools") for export of assets for use with all Havok products from Autodesk 3ds Max, Autodesk Maya, and (formerly) Autodesk Softimage.
[src:physx/havok-software] Havok was also used in the virtual world *Second Life*, with all physics handled by its online simulator servers, rather than by the users' client computers.
[src:physx/havok-software] An upgrade to Havok version 4 was released in April 2008 and an upgrade to version 7 started in June 2010.
[src:physx/havok-software] *Second Life* resident Emilin Nakamori constructed a weight-driven, pendulum-regulated mechanical clock functioning entirely by Havok Physics in March 2019.
[src:physx/havok-software] In 2025, Havok introduced a new pricing model targeting smaller and indie game developers, offering access to Havok Physics and Havok Navigation for a one-time, per-title fee.
[src:physx/physics-engine] A **physics engine** is computer software that provides an approximate simulation of certain physical systems, typically classical dynamics, including rigid body dynamics (including collision detection), soft body dynamics, and fluid dynamics.
[src:physx/physics-engine] It is of use in the domains of computer graphics, video games and film (CGI).
[src:physx/physics-engine] Their main uses are in video games (typically as middleware), in which case the simulations are in real-time.
[src:physx/physics-engine] The term is sometimes used more generally to describe any software system for simulating physical phenomena, such as high-performance scientific simulation.
[src:physx/physics-engine] There are generally two classes of physics engines: real-time and high-precision.
[src:physx/physics-engine] High-precision physics engines require more processing power to calculate very precise physics and are usually used by scientists and prerendered computer animation, such as movies.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Real-time physics engines—as used in video games and other forms of interactive computing—use simplified calculations and decreased accuracy to compute in time for the game to respond at an appropriate rate for game play.
[src:physx/physics-engine] A physics engine is essentially a big calculator that does mathematics needed to simulate physics.
[src:physx/physics-engine] One of the first general purpose computers, ENIAC, was used as a very simple type of physics engine.
[src:physx/physics-engine] It was used to design ballistics tables to help the United States military estimate where artillery shells of various mass would land when fired at varying angles and gunpowder charges, also accounting for drift caused by wind.
[src:physx/physics-engine] The results were calculated a single time only, and were tabulated into printed tables handed out to the artillery commanders.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Physics engines have been commonly used on supercomputers since the 1980s to perform computational fluid dynamics modeling, where particles are assigned force vectors that are combined to show circulation.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Due to the requirements of speed and high precision, special computer processors known as vector processors were developed to accelerate the calculations.
[src:physx/physics-engine] The techniques can be used to model weather patterns in weather forecasting, wind tunnel data for designing air- and watercraft or motor vehicles including racecars, and thermal cooling of computer processors for improving heat sinks.
[src:physx/physics-engine] As with many calculation-laden processes in computing, the accuracy of the simulation is related to the resolution of the simulation and the precision of the calculations; small fluctuations not modeled in the simulation can drastically change the predicted results.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Tire manufacturers use physics simulations to examine how new tire tread types will perform under wet and dry conditions, using new tire materials of varying flexibility and under different levels of weight loading.
[src:physx/physics-engine] The simulations optimize tire operations, material selection, costs, and enhance time efficiency.
[src:physx/physics-engine] In most computer games, speed of the processors and gameplay are more important than accuracy of simulation.
[src:physx/physics-engine] This leads to designs for physics engines that produce results in real-time but that replicate real world physics only for simple cases and typically with some approximation.
[src:physx/physics-engine] More often than not, the simulation is geared towards providing a "perceptually correct" approximation rather than a real simulation.
[src:physx/physics-engine] However some game engines, such as Source, use physics in puzzles or in combat situations.
[src:physx/physics-engine] This requires more accurate physics so that, for example, the momentum of an object can knock over an obstacle or lift a sinking object.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Physically-based character animation in the past only used rigid body dynamics because they are faster and easier to calculate, but modern games and movies are starting to use soft body physics.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Soft body physics are also used for particle effects, liquids and cloth.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Some form of limited fluid dynamics simulation is sometimes provided to simulate water and other liquids as well as the flow of fire and explosions through the air.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Objects in games interact with the player, the environment, and each other.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Typically, most 3D objects in games are represented by two separate meshes or shapes.
[src:physx/physics-engine] One of these meshes is the highly complex and detailed shape visible to the player in the game, such as a vase with elegant curved and looping handles.
[src:physx/physics-engine] For purpose of speed, a second, simplified invisible mesh is used to represent the object to the physics engine so that the physics engine treats the example vase as a simple cylinder.
[src:physx/physics-engine] It would thus be impossible to insert a rod or fire a projectile through the handle holes on the vase, because the physics engine model is based on the cylinder and is unaware of the handles.
[src:physx/physics-engine] The simplified mesh used for physics processing is often referred to as the collision geometry.
[src:physx/physics-engine] This may be a bounding box, sphere, or convex hull.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Engines that use bounding boxes or bounding spheres as the final shape for collision detection are considered extremely simple.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Generally a bounding box is used for broad phase collision detection to narrow down the number of possible collisions before costly mesh on mesh collision detection is done in the narrow phase of collision detection.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Another aspect of precision in discrete collision detection involves the framerate, or the number of moments in time per second when physics is calculated.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Each frame is treated as separate from all other frames, and the space between frames is not calculated.
[src:physx/physics-engine] A low framerate and a small fast-moving object causes a situation where the object does not move smoothly through space but instead seems to teleport from one point in space to the next as each frame is calculated.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Projectiles moving at sufficiently high speeds will miss targets, if the target is small enough to fit in the gap between the calculated frames of the fast moving projectile.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Various techniques are used to overcome this flaw, such as *Second Life*'s representation of projectiles as arrows with invisible trailing tails longer than the gap in frames to collide with any object that might fit between the calculated frames.
[src:physx/physics-engine] By contrast, continuous collision detection such as in Bullet or Havok does not suffer this problem.
[src:physx/physics-engine] An alternative to using bounding box-based rigid body physics systems is to use a finite element-based system.
[src:physx/physics-engine] In such a system, a 3-dimensional, volumetric tessellation is created of the 3D object.
[src:physx/physics-engine] The tessellation results in a number of finite elements which represent aspects of the object's physical properties such as toughness, plasticity, and volume preservation.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Once constructed, the finite elements are used by a solver to model the stress within the 3D object.
[src:physx/physics-engine] The stress can be used to drive fracture, deformation and other physical effects with a high degree of realism and uniqueness.
[src:physx/physics-engine] As the number of modeled elements is increased, the engine's ability to model physical behavior increases.
[src:physx/physics-engine] The visual representation of the 3D object is altered by the finite element system through the use of a deformation shader run on the CPU or GPU.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Finite Element-based systems had been impractical for use in games due to the performance overhead and the lack of tools to create finite element representations out of 3D art objects.
[src:physx/physics-engine] James O'Brien as a part of his PhD thesis.
[src:physx/physics-engine] In the real world, physics is always active.
[src:physx/physics-engine] There is a constant Brownian motion jitter to all particles in our universe as the forces push back and forth against each other.
[src:physx/physics-engine] For a game physics engine, such constant active precision is unnecessarily wasting the limited CPU power, which can cause problems such as decreased framerate.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Thus, games may put objects to "sleep" by disabling the computation of physics on objects that have not moved a particular distance within a certain amount of time.
[src:physx/physics-engine] For example, in the 3D virtual world Second Life, if an object is resting on the floor and the object does not move beyond a minimal distance in about two seconds, then the physics calculations are disabled for the object and it becomes frozen in place.
[src:physx/physics-engine] The object remains frozen until physics processing reactivates for the object after collision occurs with some other active physical object.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Physics engines for video games typically have two core components, a collision detection/collision response system, and the dynamics simulation component responsible for solving the forces affecting the simulated objects.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Modern physics engines may also contain fluid simulations, animation control systems and asset integration tools.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Finally, hybrid methods are possible that combine aspects of the above paradigms.
[src:physx/physics-engine] A primary limit of physics engine realism is the approximated result of the constraint resolutions and collision result due to the slow convergence of algorithms.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Collision detection computed at a too low frequency can result in objects passing through each other and then being repelled with an abnormal correction force.
[src:physx/physics-engine] On the other hand, approximated results of reaction force is due to the slow convergence of typical Projected Gauss Seidel solver resulting in abnormal bouncing.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Any type of free-moving compound physics object can demonstrate this problem, but it is especially prone to affecting chain links under high tension, and wheeled objects with actively physical bearing surfaces.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Higher precision reduces the positional/force errors, but at the cost of needing greater CPU power for the calculations.
[src:physx/physics-engine] A physics processing unit (PPU) is a dedicated microprocessor designed to handle the calculations of physics, especially in the physics engine of video games.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Examples of calculations involving a PPU might include rigid body dynamics, soft body dynamics, collision detection, fluid dynamics, hair and clothing simulation, finite element analysis, and fracturing of objects.
[src:physx/physics-engine] The idea is that specialized processors offload time-consuming tasks from a computer's CPU, much like how a GPU performs graphics operations in the main CPU's place.
[src:physx/physics-engine] The term was coined by Ageia's marketing to describe their PhysX chip to consumers.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Several other technologies in the CPU-GPU spectrum have some features in common with it, although Ageia's solution was the only complete one designed, marketed, supported, and placed within a system *exclusively* as a PPU.
[src:physx/physics-engine] Hardware acceleration for physics processing is now usually provided by graphics processing units that support more general computation, a concept known as general-purpose computing on graphics processing units (GPGPU).
[src:physx/physics-engine] AMD and NVIDIA provide support for rigid body dynamics computations on their latest graphics cards.
[src:physx/physics-engine] NVIDIA's GeForce 8 series supports a GPU-based Newtonian physics acceleration technology named *Quantum Effects Technology*.
[src:physx/physics-engine] NVIDIA provides an SDK Toolkit for CUDA (Compute Unified Device Architecture) technology that offers both a low and high-level API to the GPU.
[src:physx/physics-engine] For their GPUs, AMD offers a similar SDK, called Close to Metal (CTM), which provides a thin hardware interface.
[src:physx/physics-engine] PhysX is an example of a physics engine that can use GPGPU based hardware acceleration when it is available.
[src:physx/physx] Initially, video games supporting PhysX were meant to be accelerated by PhysX PPU (expansion cards designed by Ageia).
[src:physx/physx] However, after Ageia's acquisition by Nvidia, dedicated PhysX cards have been discontinued in favor of the API being run on CUDA-enabled GeForce GPUs.
[src:physx/physx] In both cases, hardware acceleration allowed for the offloading of certain physics calculations from the CPU, allowing it to perform other tasks instead.
[src:physx/physx] PhysX and other middleware physics engines are used in many video games today because they allow game developers to save development time by not having to write their own code that implements classical mechanics (Newtonian physics) to do, for example, soft body dynamics.
[src:physx/physx] What is known today as PhysX originated as a physics simulation engine called NovodeX.
[src:physx/physx] NovodeX was a real-time middleware physics engine developed by **NovodeX AG** in the early 2000s, and initially released in 2002 commercially.
[src:physx/physx] While the name NovodeX is largely historical bygone product today, the core technology it introduced fundamentally reshaped game development and real-time physics in video games, serving as the direct architectural foundation for the industry-standard **PhysX** engine today.
[src:physx/physx] The engine was created by **NovodeX AG**, a Swiss technology group founded in 2001 by researchers and engineers from ETH Zurich (Swiss Federal Institute of Technology).
[src:physx/physx] During the 2001–2003 window, the physics middleware market was highly competitive but technologically fragmented/limited.
[src:physx/physx] NovodeX entered this landscape with a solver that prioritized extreme mathematical precision and forward-thinking hardware scaling.
[src:physx/physx] NovodeX was designed specifically to handle massive stacks of rigid bodies and complex ragdoll constraints without them collapsing.
[src:physx/physx] On March 1, 2004, the second iteration of NovodeX Physics was released for commercial use.
[src:physx/physx] NovodeX Physics stood out as a remarkably dependable tool for calculating game physics at the time.
[src:physx/physx] NovodeX was programmed entirely in the standard C++ format, it was specially built to tap into the power of multi-core processors and multithreading technology.
[src:physx/physx] Rather than a single large block of code, NovodeX was a highly modular engine by design.
[src:physx/physx] To help artists actually get assets or props into the simulation, the NovodeX toolkit provided standard export plugins for popular 3D software of the era, including 3d modelling software like 3ds Max and MilkShape 3D.
[src:physx/physx] It also featured a browser and a specialized utility called "Tetmake," which was used specifically to generate meshes which were required by the Substance SDK.
[src:physx/physx] Along with the main engine, the team released a separate sandbox tool called NovodeX Rocket.
[src:physx/physx] The major turning point for NovodeX occurred during the development of **Unreal Engine 3** which launched in 2004.
[src:physx/physx] Epic Games had previously relied on MathEngine Karma to drive rigid-body dynamics, ragdolls and vehicles in Unreal Engine 2.
[src:physx/physx] However, as Karma was starting to show its age and the demands for next-generation physics grew, Epic began searching for a replacement for their next engine.
[src:physx/physx] On April 2, 2004, Epic Games officially partnered with NovodeX AG, integrating the NovodeX physics solver natively into the Unreal Engine 3 pipeline.
[src:physx/physx] This integration effectively marked the end of Karma in the Unreal ecosystem and instantly established NovodeX as the prominent AAA physics engine.
[src:physx/physx] In 2004, a fabless semiconductor company named **Ageia** was developing a dedicated hardware expansion card called the Physics Processing Unit (PPU).
[src:physx/physx] For this specific project Ageia needed a modern software API to interface with their hardware.
[src:physx/physx] Ageia recognized the superiority of the engine's multi-threaded architecture, and eventually acquired NovodeX AG.
[src:physx/physx] Following the acquisition, Ageia took the existing NovodeX codebase and rebranded it as Ageia **PhysX SDK**.
[src:physx/physx] The Swiss development team was retained, and continuing to build upon the original NovodeX solver to add hardware acceleration, fluid dynamics, and soft-body physics..
[src:physx/physx] Ageia would also acquire Meqon in 2005 to integrate into the PhysX engine.
[src:physx/physx] NovodeX is a prime example of a university research project turning into a massive success for the video game industry.
[src:physx/physx] In 2008, NVIDIA bought the company eventually acquired Ageia and updated the software so it could run directly on NVIDIA's graphics cards, which turned it into what is now called the PhysX engine.
[src:physx/physx] Today, whether a game is built in Unity, Unreal Engine, or by a AAA studio, the in-game physics are still driven by the same mathematics of the original NovodeX back in 2002-2004.
[src:physx/physx] In 2008, Ageia was itself acquired by graphics technology manufacturer Nvidia.
[src:physx/physx] Nvidia started enabling PhysX hardware acceleration on its line of GeForce graphics cards and eventually dropped support for Ageia PPUs.
[src:physx/physx] Nvidia PhysX SDK 3.0 was released in May 2011 and represented a significant rewrite of the SDK, bringing improvements such as more efficient multithreading and a unified code base for all supported platforms.
[src:physx/physx] At GDC 2015, Nvidia made the source code for PhysX available on GitHub, but required registration at developer.nvidia.com.
[src:physx/physx] The proprietary SDK was provided to developers for free for both commercial and non-commercial use on Windows, Linux, macOS, iOS and Android platforms.
[src:physx/physx] On December 3, 2018, PhysX was made open source under a 3-clause BSD license, but this change applied only to computer and mobile platforms.
[src:physx/physx] On November 8, 2022, the open source release was updated to PhysX 5, under the same 3-clause BSD license.
[src:physx/physx] In February 2025, support for 32-bit CUDA applications was deprecated for the GeForce RTX 50 series, rendering GPU-accelerated PhysX nonfunctional in 32-bit titles.
[src:physx/physx] This resulted in GPU PhysX options to be processed by the CPU when enabled, causing a degradation in performance, in titles such as *Mirror's Edge* and *Borderlands 2*.
[src:physx/physx] On December 4th 2025, support for select games with 32-Bit GPU-Accelerated PhysX options was implemented by Nvidia.
[src:physx/physx] The PhysX engine and SDK are available for Microsoft Windows, macOS, Linux, PlayStation 3, PlayStation 4, Xbox 360, Xbox One, Wii, iOS and Android.
[src:physx/physx] PhysX is a multi-threaded physics simulation SDK.
[src:physx/physx] It supports rigid body dynamics, soft body dynamics (like cloth simulation, including tearing and pressurized cloth), ragdolls and character controllers, vehicle dynamics, particles and volumetric fluid simulation.
[src:physx/physx] A physics processing unit (PPU) is a processor specially designed to alleviate the calculation burden on the CPU, specifically calculations involving physics.
[src:physx/physx] PhysX PPUs were offered to consumers in the forms of PCI or PCIe cards by ASUS, BFG Technologies, Dell and ELSA Technology.
[src:physx/physx] Beginning with version 2.8.3 of the PhysX SDK, support for PPU cards was dropped, and PPU cards are no longer manufactured.
[src:physx/physx] The last incarnation of PhysX PPU standalone card designed by Ageia had roughly the same PhysX performance as a dedicated 9800GTX.
[src:physx/physx] After Nvidia's acquisition of Ageia, PhysX development turned away from PPU expansion cards and focused instead on the GPGPU capabilities of modern GPUs.
[src:physx/physx] Modern GPUs are very efficient at manipulating and displaying computer graphics, and their highly parallel structure makes them more effective than general-purpose CPUs for accelerating physical simulations using PhysX.
[src:physx/physx] Any CUDA-ready GeForce graphics card (8-series or later GPU with a minimum of 32 cores and a minimum of 256 MB dedicated graphics memory) can take advantage of PhysX without the need to install a dedicated PhysX card.
[src:physx/physx] Nvidia APEX technology is a multi-platform scalable dynamics framework build around the PhysX SDK.
[src:physx/physx] It was first introduced in *Mafia II* in August 2010.
[src:physx/physx] Nvidia's APEX comprises the following modules: APEX Destruction, APEX Clothing, APEX Particles, APEX Turbulence, APEX ForceField and formerly APEX Vegetation which was suspended in 2011.
[src:physx/physx] From version 1.4.1 APEX SDK is deprecated.
[src:physx/physx] FleX is a particle based simulation technique for real-time visual effects.
[src:physx/physx] Traditionally, visual effects are made using a combination of elements created using specialized solvers for rigid bodies, fluids, clothing, etc.
[src:physx/physx] Because FleX uses a unified particle representation for all object types, it enables new effects where different simulated substances can interact with each other seamlessly.
[src:physx/physx] Such unified physics solvers are a staple of the offline computer graphics world, where tools such as Autodesk Maya's nCloth, and Softimage's Lagoa are widely used.
[src:physx/physx] The goal for FleX is to use the power of GPUs to bring the capabilities of these offline applications to real-time computer graphics.
[src:physx/physx] On July 5, 2010, Real World Technologies published an analysis of the PhysX architecture.
[src:physx/physx] According to this analysis, most of the code used in PhysX applications at the time was based on x87 instructions without any multithreading optimization.
[src:physx/physx] This could cause significant performance drops when running PhysX code on the CPU.
[src:physx/physx] The article suggested that a PhysX rewrite using SSE instructions may substantially lessen the performance discrepancy between CPU PhysX and GPU PhysX.
[src:physx/physx] In response to the Real World Technologies analysis, Mike Skolones, product manager of PhysX, said that SSE support had been left behind because most games are developed for consoles first and then ported to the PC.
[src:physx/physx] As a result, modern computers run these games faster and better than the consoles even with little or no optimization.
[src:physx/physx] Senior PR manager of Nvidia, Bryan Del Rizzo, explained that multithreading had already been available with CPU PhysX 2.x and that it had been up to the developer to make use of it.
[src:physx/physx] He also stated that automatic multithreading and SSE would be introduced with version 3 of the PhysX SDK.
[src:physx/physx] PhysX SDK 3.0 was released in May 2011 and represented a significant rewrite of the SDK, bringing improvements such as more efficient multithreading and a unified code base for all supported platforms.
[src:physx/physx] PhysX technology is used by game engines such as Unreal Engine (version 3 onwards), Unity, Gamebryo, Vision (version 6 onwards), Instinct Engine, Panda3D, Diesel, Torque, HeroEngine, and BigWorld.
[src:physx/physx] As one of the handful of major physics engines, it is used in many games, such as *The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt*, *Warframe*, *Killing Floor 2*, *Batman: Arkham Knight*, *Planetside 2,*and *Borderlands 2*.
[src:physx/physx] Most of these games use the CPU to process the physics simulations.
[src:physx/physx] Video games with optional support for hardware-accelerated PhysX often include additional effects such as tearable cloth, dynamic smoke or simulated particle debris.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] In classical mechanics, **rigid body dynamics** studies the movement of systems of interconnected bodies under the action of external forces.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Along with statics, it forms the field of **rigid body mechanics**.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The assumption that the bodies are *rigid* (i.e. they do not deform under the action of applied forces) simplifies analysis, by reducing the parameters that describe the configuration of the system to the translation and rotation of body-fixed frames.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] This excludes bodies that display fluid, highly elastic, and plastic behavior.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The dynamics of a rigid body system is described by the laws of kinematics and by the application of Newton's second law (kinetics) or their derivative form, Lagrangian mechanics.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The solution of these equations of motion provides a description of the position, the motion and the acceleration of the individual components of the system, and overall the system itself, as a function of time.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The formulation and solution of rigid body dynamics is an important tool in the computer simulation of mechanical systems.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] If a system of particles moves parallel to a fixed plane, the system is said to be constrained to planar movement.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] In this case, Newton's laws (kinetics) for a rigid system of N particles, P*i*, *i*=1,...,*N*, simplify because there is no movement in the *k* direction.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] where **r**i denotes the planar trajectory of each particle.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] For systems that are constrained to planar movement, the angular velocity and angular acceleration vectors are directed along **k** perpendicular to the plane of movement, which simplifies this acceleration equation.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] where ${\textstyle \mathbf {e} _{i}\times \mathbf {e} _{i}=0}$ and ${\textstyle \mathbf {e} _{i}\times \mathbf {t} _{i}=\mathbf {k} }$ is the unit vector perpendicular to the plane for all of the particles Pi.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] where M is the total mass and *I***C** is the moment of inertia about an axis perpendicular to the movement of the rigid system and through the center of mass.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Several methods to describe orientations of a rigid body in three dimensions have been developed.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] They are summarized in the following sections.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The first attempt to represent an orientation is attributed to Leonhard Euler.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The values of these three rotations are called Euler angles.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Commonly, $\psi$ is used to denote precession, $\theta$ nutation, and $\phi$ intrinsic rotation.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] These are three angles, also known as yaw, pitch and roll, Navigation angles and Cardan angles.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Mathematically they constitute a set of six possibilities inside the twelve possible sets of Euler angles, the ordering being the one best used for describing the orientation of a vehicle such as an airplane.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] In aerospace engineering they are usually referred to as Euler angles.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Euler also realized that the composition of two rotations is equivalent to a single rotation about a different fixed axis (Euler's rotation theorem).
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, the composition of the former three angles has to be equal to only one rotation, whose axis was complicated to calculate until matrices were developed.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Based on this fact he introduced a vectorial way to describe any rotation, with a vector on the rotation axis and module equal to the value of the angle.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, any orientation can be represented by a rotation vector (also called Euler vector) that leads to it from the reference frame.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent an orientation, the rotation vector is commonly called orientation vector, or attitude vector.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] A similar method, called axis-angle representation, describes a rotation or orientation using a unit vector aligned with the rotation axis, and a separate value to indicate the angle (see figure).
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] With the introduction of matrices the Euler theorems were rewritten.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The rotations were described by orthogonal matrices referred to as rotation matrices or direction cosine matrices.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent an orientation, a rotation matrix is commonly called orientation matrix, or attitude matrix.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The above-mentioned Euler vector is the eigenvector of a rotation matrix (a rotation matrix has a unique real eigenvalue).
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The product of two rotation matrices is the composition of rotations.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, as before, the orientation can be given as the rotation from the initial frame to achieve the frame that we want to describe.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The configuration space of a non-symmetrical object in *n*-dimensional space is SO(*n*) × **R***n*.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Orientation may be visualized by attaching a basis of tangent vectors to an object.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The direction in which each vector points determines its orientation.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Another way to describe rotations is using rotation quaternions, also called versors.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] They are equivalent to rotation matrices and rotation vectors.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] With respect to rotation vectors, they can be more easily converted to and from matrices.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent orientations, rotation quaternions are typically called orientation quaternions or attitude quaternions.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] To consider rigid body dynamics in three-dimensional space, Newton's second law must be extended to define the relationship between the movement of a rigid body and the system of forces and torques that act on it.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The extension of Newton's second law to rigid bodies is achieved by considering a rigid system of particles.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] If a system of *N* particles, Pi, i=1,...,*N*, are assembled into a rigid body, then Newton's second law can be applied to each of the particles in the body.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] An important simplification to these force equations is obtained by introducing the resultant force and torque that acts on the rigid system.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] This resultant force and torque is obtained by choosing one of the particles in the system as a reference point, **R**, where each of the external forces are applied with the addition of an associated torque.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The resultant force **F** and torque **T** are given by the formulas, $\mathbf {F} =\sum _{i=1}^{N}\mathbf {F} _{i},\quad \mathbf {T} =\sum _{i=1}^{N}(\mathbf {R} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )\times \mathbf {F} _{i},$ where **R**i is the vector that defines the position of particle Pi.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The mass properties of the rigid body are represented by its center of mass and inertia matrix.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] then it is known as the center of mass of the system.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] where $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ is the column vector **R**i − **R**; $\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}$ is its transpose, and $\mathbf {I}$ is the 3 by 3 identity matrix.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] $\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}\mathbf {S} _{i}$ is the scalar product of $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ with itself, while $\mathbf {S} _{i}\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}$ is the tensor product of $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ with itself.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Using the center of mass and inertia matrix, the force and torque equations for a single rigid body take the form $\mathbf {F} =m\mathbf {a} ,\quad \mathbf {T} =[I_{R}]\alpha +\omega \times [I_{R}]\omega ,$ and are known as Newton's second law of motion for a rigid body.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The dynamics of an interconnected system of rigid bodies, *B**i*, *j* = 1, ..., *M*, is formulated by isolating each rigid body and introducing the interaction forces.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Newton's formulation yields 6*M* equations that define the dynamics of a system of *M* rigid bodies.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] A rotating object, whether under the influence of torques or not, may exhibit the behaviours of precession and nutation.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The solution to this equation when there is no applied torque is discussed in the articles Euler's equation of motion and Poinsot's ellipsoid.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] It follows from Euler's equation that a torque **τ** applied perpendicular to the axis of rotation, and therefore perpendicular to **L**, results in a rotation about an axis perpendicular to both **τ** and **L**.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Precession can be demonstrated by placing a spinning top with its axis horizontal and supported loosely (frictionless toward precession) at one end.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Instead of falling, as might be expected, the top appears to defy gravity by remaining with its axis horizontal, when the other end of the axis is left unsupported and the free end of the axis slowly describes a circle in a horizontal plane, the resulting precession turning.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] This effect is explained by the above equations.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The torque on the top is supplied by a couple of forces: gravity acting downward on the device's centre of mass, and an equal force acting upward to support one end of the device.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Under a constant torque of magnitude *τ*, the speed of precession *Ω*P is inversely proportional to *L*, the magnitude of its angular momentum: $\tau ={\mathit {\Omega }}_{\mathrm {P} }L\sin \theta ,$ where *θ* is the angle between the vectors **Ω**P and **L**.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Thus, if the top's spin slows down (for example, due to friction), its angular momentum decreases and so the rate of precession increases.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] This continues until the device is unable to rotate fast enough to support its own weight, when it stops precessing and falls off its support, mostly because friction against precession cause another precession that goes to cause the fall.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] By convention, these three vectors – torque, spin, and precession – are all oriented with respect to each other according to the right-hand rule.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] An alternate formulation of rigid body dynamics that has a number of convenient features is obtained by considering the virtual work of forces acting on a rigid body.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The virtual work of forces acting at various points on a single rigid body can be calculated using the velocities of their point of application and the resultant force and torque.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The trajectories of **R***i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n* are defined by the movement of the rigid body.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The velocity of the points **R***i* along their trajectories are $\mathbf {V} _{i}={\boldsymbol {\omega }}\times (\mathbf {R} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {V} ,$ where **ω** is the angular velocity vector of the body.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] is known as the generalized force associated with the virtual displacement δq.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] It is useful to note that conservative forces such as gravity and spring forces are derivable from a potential function *V*(*q*1, ..., *q**n*), known as a potential energy.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The equations of motion for a mechanical system of rigid bodies can be determined using D'Alembert's form of the principle of virtual work.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The principle of virtual work is used to study the static equilibrium of a system of rigid bodies; however, by introducing acceleration terms in Newton's laws this approach is generalized to define dynamic equilibrium.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The static equilibrium of a mechanical system rigid bodies is defined by the condition that the virtual work of the applied forces is zero for any virtual displacement of the system.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] This is known as the *principle of virtual work.* This is equivalent to the requirement that the generalized forces for any virtual displacement are zero, that is *Q**i*=0.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Let a mechanical system be constructed from n rigid bodies, B*i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*, and let the resultant of the applied forces on each body be the force-torque pairs, **F***i* and **T***i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Notice that these applied forces do not include the reaction forces where the bodies are connected.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Finally, assume that the velocity **V***i* and angular velocities ***ω****i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*, for each rigid body, are defined by a single generalized coordinate q.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Such a system of rigid bodies is said to have one degree of freedom.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] These m equations define the static equilibrium of the system of rigid bodies.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Consider a single rigid body which moves under the action of a resultant force **F** and torque **T**, with one degree of freedom defined by the generalized coordinate *q*.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] D'Alembert's form of the principle of virtual work states that a system of rigid bodies is in dynamic equilibrium when the virtual work of the sum of the applied forces and the inertial forces is zero for any virtual displacement of the system.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Thus, dynamic equilibrium of a system of n rigid bodies with m generalized coordinates requires that $\delta W=\left(Q_{1}+Q_{1}^{*}\right)\delta q_{1}+\dots +\left(Q_{m}+Q_{m}^{*}\right)\delta q_{m}=0,$ for any set of virtual displacements *δq**j*.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] In this case, introduce the Lagrangian, *L* = *T* − *V*, so these equations of motion become ${\frac {d}{dt}}{\frac {\partial L}{\partial {\dot {q}}_{j}}}-{\frac {\partial L}{\partial q_{j}}}=0\quad j=1,\ldots ,m.$ These are known as Lagrange's equations of motion.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] The linear and angular momentum of a rigid system of particles is formulated by measuring the position and velocity of the particles relative to the center of mass.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Let the system of particles Pi, *i* = 1, ..., *n* be located at the coordinates **r***i* and velocities **v***i*.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] To specialize these formulas to a rigid body, assume the particles are rigidly connected to each other so Pi, i=1,...,n are located by the coordinates **r**i and velocities **v**i.
[src:physx/rigid-body-dynamics] Select a reference point **R** and compute the relative position and velocity vectors, $\mathbf {r} _{i}=(\mathbf {r} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {R} ,\quad \mathbf {v} _{i}=\omega \times (\mathbf {r} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {V} ,$ where ω is the angular velocity of the system.
